WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.950 --> 00:00:01.830
Prof: Okay,
I think I'll start.

00:00:01.830 --> 00:00:05.240
So we considered for a long
time a world of certainty.

00:00:05.240 --> 00:00:08.340
Hope something's okay.
 

00:00:08.340 --> 00:00:11.621
Considered a world of certainty
where we assumed we could

00:00:11.621 --> 00:00:15.077
foresee the future perfectly,
and we still managed to figure

00:00:15.077 --> 00:00:17.070
out fairly interesting things.
 

00:00:17.070 --> 00:00:20.350
But the world is much more
complicated than that.

00:00:20.350 --> 00:00:24.709
It's a world of uncertainty,
and in a world of uncertainty,

00:00:24.709 --> 00:00:28.768
economics comes into its own,
I think, as a fascinating

00:00:28.768 --> 00:00:29.670
subject.
 

00:00:29.670 --> 00:00:32.540
So I spent a little time
reviewing some mathematics for

00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:35.040
you last time that many of you
already knew,

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:39.048
so I'm going to take that for
granted going forward and just

00:00:39.048 --> 00:00:41.364
start over,
this time from an economic

00:00:41.364 --> 00:00:44.040
perspective instead of a
mathematical perspective.

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:50.713
So suppose today that we assume
that you could buy a stock today

00:00:50.713 --> 00:00:55.904
whose price tomorrow could be
104 or 98 with 50:50

00:00:55.904 --> 00:01:01.201
probabilities and we assume that
everybody knew the

00:01:01.201 --> 00:01:03.320
probabilities.
 

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:19.016
Know probabilities and maximize
expected payoff next period,

00:01:19.016 --> 00:01:20.879
okay?
 

00:01:20.879 --> 00:01:30.590
Well, payoff this period.
 

00:01:30.590 --> 00:01:32.810
If we assumed--and we're going
to drop this assumption,

00:01:32.810 --> 00:01:34.300
but I'm going to keep it for a
little while--

00:01:34.300 --> 00:01:37.114
if we assumed that all people
cared about was their expected

00:01:37.114 --> 00:01:39.977
payoff next period and of course
they care about their payoff

00:01:39.977 --> 00:01:42.428
this period,
what would the value of the

00:01:42.428 --> 00:01:43.519
stock have to be?
 

00:01:43.519 --> 00:01:47.602
Well, under the simple rule for
how people act,

00:01:47.602 --> 00:01:51.417
you'd take 1 half times 104 1
half times 98,

00:01:51.417 --> 00:01:56.209
and that would give you--what
would that give you?

00:01:56.209 --> 00:02:00.924
It'd give you 101,
okay, because this is 4 times 1

00:02:00.924 --> 00:02:04.632
half is 2;
- 2 times 1 half which is - 1,

00:02:04.632 --> 00:02:07.608
so it's 1, so that'd give you
101.

00:02:07.608 --> 00:02:10.768
So you would say that the price
of the stock today would have to

00:02:10.768 --> 00:02:11.218
be 101.
 

00:02:11.218 --> 00:02:16.281
Now we could slightly refine
this utility function and say

00:02:16.281 --> 00:02:21.697
people maximize the discounted
expected payoff next period the

00:02:21.697 --> 00:02:23.740
payoff this period.
 

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:31.319
And if the discount is 100 over
101, then we're going to have to

00:02:31.319 --> 00:02:38.660
multiply this by 100 over 101
and we'll get a price of 100.

00:02:38.660 --> 00:02:41.530
Okay, so that's the basic first
step.

00:02:41.530 --> 00:02:45.022
We can incorporate uncertainty
by assuming people replace the

00:02:45.022 --> 00:02:48.400
uncertain outcomes with certain
outcomes in their head,

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:51.120
and then discount,
just like we've seen before.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:53.264
Of course, before we had
utility functions but I'm not

00:02:53.264 --> 00:02:54.440
going to do that quite yet.
 

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:57.663
I'm just going to say,
suppose that we just did that,

00:02:57.663 --> 00:02:58.160
right?
 

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:01.865
That would give us a theory of
how people manage uncertainty

00:03:01.865 --> 00:03:05.318
and react to uncertainty and how
they set the prices.

00:03:05.318 --> 00:03:09.825
So it's the
expected--expectation theory of

00:03:09.825 --> 00:03:10.900
pricing.
 

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:15.141
Now before we complicate the
theory, I want to just take this

00:03:15.141 --> 00:03:18.889
literally as true and make some
inferences from it.

00:03:18.889 --> 00:03:30.264
Well, the first inference you
can make is that today's price

00:03:30.264 --> 00:03:42.410
would then be the discounted
expectation of tomorrow's price.

00:03:42.410 --> 00:03:47.455
That's just repeating the same
thing, but what's an implication

00:03:47.455 --> 00:03:48.270
of that?
 

00:03:48.270 --> 00:03:57.127
The implication of that is,
if you didn't know tomorrow's

00:03:57.127 --> 00:04:04.562
price, know the expectation of
tomorrow's price,

00:04:04.562 --> 00:04:09.938
you could guess today's price.
 

00:04:09.938 --> 00:04:12.378
I'm writing out this trivial
thought because it's such an

00:04:12.378 --> 00:04:13.120
important idea.
 

00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:16.269
Once you have a theory of how
prices formed,

00:04:16.269 --> 00:04:18.860
you can always go backwards,
and as the naive,

00:04:18.860 --> 00:04:24.129
uninformed member of a society,
you can learn,

00:04:24.129 --> 00:04:25.829
instead of learning about the
stocks,

00:04:25.829 --> 00:04:27.519
you can learn all you need to
learn,

00:04:27.519 --> 00:04:29.180
perhaps, by looking at the
price.

00:04:29.180 --> 00:04:32.024
You may be interested in what
the expected value of the stock

00:04:32.024 --> 00:04:32.829
is next period.
 

00:04:32.829 --> 00:04:35.949
To do that in a serious way,
you'd have to study the firm,

00:04:35.949 --> 00:04:38.810
study the product,
study the new inventions,

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:41.569
the new technologies it was
trying to adopt,

00:04:41.569 --> 00:04:43.819
get some idea of the quality of
the manager.

00:04:43.819 --> 00:04:46.540
You'd have to do a million
things to figure that out.

00:04:46.540 --> 00:04:50.083
But if you just look at the
price today, maybe that's going

00:04:50.083 --> 00:04:53.809
to give you a good idea of what
the expected value of the firm

00:04:53.809 --> 00:04:54.970
is next period.
 

00:04:54.970 --> 00:05:02.206
And that's another way--that
also implies you can test the

00:05:02.206 --> 00:05:03.350
theory.
 

00:05:03.350 --> 00:05:07.142
Is it true that typically
today's price is a good forecast

00:05:07.142 --> 00:05:10.670
of the price tomorrow,
the expected price tomorrow?

00:05:10.670 --> 00:05:13.519
Obviously you can't just look
at one instance,

00:05:13.519 --> 00:05:15.649
because you would just be
looking--if things went up,

00:05:15.649 --> 00:05:19.014
you'd be just looking at the
104, and 100 wouldn't be a good

00:05:19.014 --> 00:05:19.870
guess of 104.
 

00:05:19.870 --> 00:05:22.369
But if you did this the next
day, and things were

00:05:22.369 --> 00:05:23.908
independent,
on the second day,

00:05:23.908 --> 00:05:26.363
of the first day,
you'd have a new price,

00:05:26.363 --> 00:05:29.160
104 the next day,
and you could see whether the

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:30.639
price went up or down or not.
 

00:05:30.639 --> 00:05:33.863
And by doing this 1,000 times
or 100,000 times,

00:05:33.863 --> 00:05:37.786
you'd get a good idea if,
on average, today's price was a

00:05:37.786 --> 00:05:41.009
pretty good predictor of
tomorrow's price.

00:05:41.009 --> 00:05:55.350
So here's the--I did that
experiment and here it is.

00:05:55.350 --> 00:05:57.060
Why is this so small?
 

00:05:57.060 --> 00:05:59.920
Okay, so from 1980--I didn't do
this.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:05.410
I got someone this morning to
do this at my hedge fund.

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:06.720
So what did he do?
 

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:11.403
He said, suppose you had 1
dollar to put in each day

00:06:11.403 --> 00:06:16.672
starting in 1980,
you could keep track of how

00:06:16.672 --> 00:06:20.216
many dollars--
say you had 100 dollars,

00:06:20.216 --> 00:06:21.649
so it's 100 dollars.
 

00:06:21.649 --> 00:06:27.540
You have 100 dollars to invest
each day, starting January

00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:29.120
1^(st), 1980.
 

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:31.490
You put it into the S&amp;P
500,

00:06:31.490 --> 00:06:34.100
so you put it equally into all
stocks,

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:37.221
the 500 biggest stocks,
and you see what the total

00:06:37.221 --> 00:06:40.089
price of those 500 stocks is the
next day,

00:06:40.089 --> 00:06:42.819
and you subtract the original
price,

00:06:42.819 --> 00:06:48.199
and that gives you your percent
return on the first day.

00:06:48.199 --> 00:06:49.442
For example,
if it was 101,

00:06:49.442 --> 00:06:51.928
it seems like it went up a
little bit, you'd have a 1

00:06:51.928 --> 00:06:54.560
percent--you'd have made 1
dollar in the first day.

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:57.550
Then I told the guy,
or he decided himself,

00:06:57.550 --> 00:07:01.303
put 100 dollars in the second
day, in the S&amp;P 500 and see

00:07:01.303 --> 00:07:03.620
what happened to that the next
day.

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:05.579
Maybe it went up 3 dollars the
second day.

00:07:05.579 --> 00:07:09.199
So your total after 2 days
would be 4 dollars.

00:07:09.199 --> 00:07:11.086
Not your total return,
although that's how he's

00:07:11.086 --> 00:07:11.620
written it.
 

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:14.800
It's just the first day,
the stock when up by 1 dollar,

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:17.040
the 100 dollars went up by 1
dollar.

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:19.829
The second day it went up by 3
dollars, so altogether,

00:07:19.829 --> 00:07:21.199
it went up by 4 dollars.
 

00:07:21.199 --> 00:07:25.327
So the hypothesis is that
today's price is a good forecast

00:07:25.327 --> 00:07:26.920
of tomorrow's price.
 

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:30.083
So if you're averaging the 's
and -'s over many days,

00:07:30.083 --> 00:07:33.672
so there are 250 days for 30
years here, that' a lot of days

00:07:33.672 --> 00:07:34.949
you're averaging.
 

00:07:34.949 --> 00:07:41.949
And this is the cumulative
total of what would have

00:07:41.949 --> 00:07:45.310
happened to you,
okay?

00:07:45.310 --> 00:07:50.158
Well, that 100 dollars,
if you did that experiment

00:07:50.158 --> 00:07:53.920
7,000 times, you know,
30 times 250.

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:59.353
30 times 250 is 7,500 times,
you would have ended up with

00:07:59.353 --> 00:08:02.459
350 or 400 dollars by the end.
 

00:08:02.459 --> 00:08:06.617
So does that contradict or
confirm the hypothesis that

00:08:06.617 --> 00:08:10.069
we've just made,
that today's price is a good

00:08:10.069 --> 00:08:14.149
forecast of the expectation of
tomorrow's price?

00:08:14.149 --> 00:08:15.509
What would you say?
 

00:08:15.509 --> 00:08:26.470
Student:
&gt;

00:08:26.470 --> 00:08:28.899
Prof: Okay,
well, so that's a subtle

00:08:28.899 --> 00:08:29.420
answer.
 

00:08:29.420 --> 00:08:32.017
So there are two things that I
expected you to say,

00:08:32.017 --> 00:08:34.769
that one being the second and a
very important one.

00:08:34.769 --> 00:08:40.181
It looks like 100 dollars
became 400 dollars,

00:08:40.181 --> 00:08:47.558
but that was over 30 years,
so what was the gain per year?

00:08:47.558 --> 00:08:52.076
7,500 days, and you got a
return of 250 percent,

00:08:52.076 --> 00:08:56.880
so you have to divide 250 by
7,500 and you get some

00:08:56.880 --> 00:08:59.379
incredibly low number.
 

00:08:59.379 --> 00:09:06.778
I forgot what it was,
but it was something like .0047

00:09:06.778 --> 00:09:11.190
percent, something like that.
 

00:09:11.190 --> 00:09:14.730
So you're making--so this is
percent.

00:09:14.730 --> 00:09:21.289
I've already divided by 100 to
turn it into percentages.

00:09:21.289 --> 00:09:23.759
So you make a tiny return.
 

00:09:23.759 --> 00:09:27.614
On 100 dollars,
you might go up on average the

00:09:27.614 --> 00:09:30.870
next day to 100 and 1 half
dollars,

00:09:30.870 --> 00:09:35.990
but that's making it--but this
.0047 percent,

00:09:35.990 --> 00:09:40.570
so 1 dollar would be 1 percent,
there would be a 1 here,

00:09:40.570 --> 00:09:42.720
but we've got a lot of decimal
places there.

00:09:42.720 --> 00:09:45.820
So you're dividing 250 by 7,500.
 

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:47.649
Maybe I've got one decimal too
many there.

00:09:47.649 --> 00:09:49.139
So this is a tiny number.
 

00:09:49.139 --> 00:09:52.596
So in fact today's price is a
pretty good estimate of

00:09:52.596 --> 00:09:53.860
tomorrow's price.
 

00:09:53.860 --> 00:09:59.833
You have 100 dollars and maybe
it will turn in on average to

00:09:59.833 --> 00:10:02.668
100.0047 dollars tomorrow.
 

00:10:02.668 --> 00:10:06.625
So compared to knowing nothing,
if you asked yourself what's

00:10:06.625 --> 00:10:09.509
the average value of this stock
tomorrow?

00:10:09.509 --> 00:10:11.759
No one's telling you it's
normalized at 100.

00:10:11.759 --> 00:10:14.201
It could be 500,
it could be 23,

00:10:14.201 --> 00:10:15.538
it could be 75.
 

00:10:15.538 --> 00:10:17.788
Who knows what the average of
these stocks are?

00:10:17.788 --> 00:10:20.947
The S&amp;P 500 are mixing
stocks that are worth 3 with

00:10:20.947 --> 00:10:24.514
stocks that are worth 500 per
share with stocks that are worth

00:10:24.514 --> 00:10:25.509
75 per share.
 

00:10:25.509 --> 00:10:29.798
And it turns out that it's such
an accurate predictor that you

00:10:29.798 --> 00:10:33.384
only are off by a fraction of 1
percent, on average,

00:10:33.384 --> 00:10:34.298
each day.
 

00:10:34.298 --> 00:10:37.471
So compared to knowing nothing,
you have a huge insight into

00:10:37.471 --> 00:10:40.644
what's going on in the world and
how valuable the stocks are

00:10:40.644 --> 00:10:41.990
going to be tomorrow.
 

00:10:41.990 --> 00:10:43.230
Tomorrow hasn't happened yet.
 

00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:44.976
Already by looking at the
prices today,

00:10:44.976 --> 00:10:47.779
you have a tremendous idea of
what the prices are tomorrow.

00:10:47.779 --> 00:10:50.695
So that's the first thing to
notice, the theory's kind of

00:10:50.695 --> 00:10:51.320
confirmed.
 

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:54.186
The second thing to notice as
well, it doesn't seem perfectly

00:10:54.186 --> 00:10:57.100
confirmed, because this seems
like a pretty positive thing.

00:10:57.100 --> 00:10:59.923
You know, it seems to be going
up most of the time,

00:10:59.923 --> 00:11:02.520
and as he said,
"Well, we haven't done the

00:11:02.520 --> 00:11:03.990
discounting yet."
 

00:11:03.990 --> 00:11:06.669
We should have done
discounting, because tomorrow is

00:11:06.669 --> 00:11:09.980
not quite as important to you as
today, so I shouldn't have just

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:11.399
been looking at return.
 

00:11:11.399 --> 00:11:15.019
I should have looked at return
per day.

00:11:15.019 --> 00:11:22.005
So I should have discounted
each day by whatever the

00:11:22.005 --> 00:11:24.610
interest rate is.
 

00:11:24.610 --> 00:11:27.490
Let's say you think it's 4
percent in a year,

00:11:27.490 --> 00:11:30.500
divided by 250,
since there are 250 days in the

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:31.090
year.
 

00:11:31.090 --> 00:11:33.538
So approximately,
I should have gotten 250,

00:11:33.538 --> 00:11:35.580
I should have discounted by
that.

00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:39.075
So when you do that,
the number gets even much

00:11:39.075 --> 00:11:41.745
closer to 0,
but it doesn't come exactly

00:11:41.745 --> 00:11:45.260
equal to 0 and so we're going to
see that we need something else

00:11:45.260 --> 00:11:46.879
to make up the difference.
 

00:11:46.879 --> 00:11:50.440
But it's such a tiny difference
that needs explaining.

00:11:50.440 --> 00:11:52.658
So to summarize,
we have this view that

00:11:52.658 --> 00:11:56.160
uncertainty is going to change
everything that we think about

00:11:56.160 --> 00:11:59.840
the world and it will change a
lot of things dramatically,

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:03.399
but it's not going to change
the idea that today,

00:12:03.399 --> 00:12:06.722
the price today of things is a
pretty good indicator of what

00:12:06.722 --> 00:12:08.918
their value is going to be
tomorrow,

00:12:08.918 --> 00:12:11.649
if you replace value tomorrow,
which is uncertain,

00:12:11.649 --> 00:12:14.210
by the expected value tomorrow.
 

00:12:14.210 --> 00:12:16.743
So you can still learn a
tremendous amount about the

00:12:16.743 --> 00:12:18.678
world, just by looking at the
market.

00:12:18.678 --> 00:12:24.250
That's a very important lesson,
so let's go a little further

00:12:24.250 --> 00:12:25.100
though.
 

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:30.952
Suppose that you thought,
well, maybe people--maybe I

00:12:30.952 --> 00:12:35.678
want to ask a more complicated
question.

00:12:35.678 --> 00:12:40.504
I want to say,
suppose I only look at stocks

00:12:40.504 --> 00:12:43.308
that went up yesterday.
 

00:12:43.308 --> 00:12:46.428
I only look at stocks that went
up yesterday.

00:12:46.428 --> 00:12:49.721
Now maybe there's something
about the market that,

00:12:49.721 --> 00:12:53.216
you know, momentum will keep
carrying those stocks up

00:12:53.216 --> 00:12:54.090
tomorrow.
 

00:12:54.090 --> 00:12:56.979
So once the market gets
rolling, maybe the market's not

00:12:56.979 --> 00:12:58.210
such a good forecast.
 

00:12:58.210 --> 00:13:00.337
Maybe, as Shiller says,
there are all these

00:13:00.337 --> 00:13:03.410
psychological forces at work,
and once things get rolling and

00:13:03.410 --> 00:13:07.562
prices have gone up yesterday,
the price will keep going up

00:13:07.562 --> 00:13:08.509
tomorrow.
 

00:13:08.509 --> 00:13:10.937
So today's price won't be such
a good indicator of tomorrow's

00:13:10.937 --> 00:13:13.570
price, because tomorrow's price
is probably going to be higher.

00:13:13.570 --> 00:13:16.620
So I'm going to repeat now
exactly the same experiment,

00:13:16.620 --> 00:13:21.990
except instead of putting 100
dollars in all the S&amp;P 500,

00:13:21.990 --> 00:13:25.607
I'll only put the 100 dollars
into the stocks that went up

00:13:25.607 --> 00:13:26.370
yesterday.
 

00:13:26.370 --> 00:13:30.028
Or I might even refine it by
selling short the stocks that

00:13:30.028 --> 00:13:31.440
went down yesterday.
 

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:33.950
Okay, so what does that do?
 

00:13:33.950 --> 00:13:43.558
Does that change the numbers?
 

00:13:43.558 --> 00:13:46.740
So if I blow this up,
maybe it is blown up.

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:48.259
Can't do any better than that.
 

00:13:48.259 --> 00:13:50.120
Does that change the numbers?
 

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:51.840
Well, no.
 

00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:53.000
In fact, it makes it worse.
 

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.428
It's closer to 0 now.
 

00:13:55.428 --> 00:13:58.335
So again, over all this time,
it kind of went up to the same

00:13:58.335 --> 00:14:00.695
peak,
but fell down even further,

00:14:00.695 --> 00:14:03.582
so this thing--
so again, the stock prices

00:14:03.582 --> 00:14:07.230
today, even if I try to refine
it and get more clever.

00:14:07.230 --> 00:14:08.700
I try to fool the market.
 

