00:14:19.528 --> 00:14:23.274
Maybe that's not such a
good--maybe on that subset the

00:14:23.274 --> 00:14:24.899
market's not so good.
 

00:14:24.899 --> 00:14:28.240
Well, the market is pretty good
on those too.

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:32.110
So again, you have to do the
discounting and you have to

00:14:32.110 --> 00:14:35.840
realize that there are a huge
number of days here,

00:14:35.840 --> 00:14:38.259
so this tiny return is really
nothing,

00:14:38.259 --> 00:14:40.610
averaged over all those numbers
of days.

00:14:40.610 --> 00:14:44.879
Well, let's see if we can come
up with another strategy.

00:14:44.879 --> 00:14:48.279
I forgot what other strategy I
tried out here.

00:14:48.279 --> 00:14:53.282
Oh, suppose you could say,
"I want to choose only

00:14:53.282 --> 00:14:58.755
those stocks that went up 20
days ago, or 25 days ago or 14

00:14:58.755 --> 00:15:00.548
days ago."
 

00:15:00.548 --> 00:15:03.413
This number here,
these bars here,

00:15:03.413 --> 00:15:07.580
represent for everything for
the S&amp;P 500,

00:15:07.580 --> 00:15:08.990
you try to say,
"What's the

00:15:08.990 --> 00:15:09.899
correlation?"
 

00:15:09.899 --> 00:15:12.567
That's like the covariance but
normalized so it's between 0 and

00:15:12.567 --> 00:15:12.740
1.
 

00:15:12.740 --> 00:15:18.269
What's the correlation of a
move yesterday and a move today?

00:15:18.269 --> 00:15:21.792
Does the fact that a stock went
up yesterday mean that it's

00:15:21.792 --> 00:15:23.190
going to go up today?
 

00:15:23.190 --> 00:15:27.255
Or does the fact that a stock
went up three days ago mean that

00:15:27.255 --> 00:15:30.990
it's going to go up today,
between today and tomorrow?

00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:33.937
So if it went up two days
ago--if it went up yesterday,

00:15:33.937 --> 00:15:36.721
from yesterday to today,
does that suggest that it's

00:15:36.721 --> 00:15:39.070
likely to go up from today to
tomorrow?

00:15:39.070 --> 00:15:42.494
So what this says--of course,
if you only did the experiment

00:15:42.494 --> 00:15:45.279
once, you'd always find that it
did something.

00:15:45.279 --> 00:15:47.320
Okay, so you have to do many
experiments,

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:50.139
and then figure out,
it's a statistical thing,

00:15:50.139 --> 00:15:51.960
to sort of guess what the
correlation is,

00:15:51.960 --> 00:15:53.399
estimate the correlation.
 

00:15:53.399 --> 00:15:57.500
Then you have to see whether
it's significant.

00:15:57.500 --> 00:16:00.923
So anything in this blue band
means the numbers are

00:16:00.923 --> 00:16:02.019
insignificant.
 

00:16:02.019 --> 00:16:05.470
So these bars represent what
the correlation is.

00:16:05.470 --> 00:16:10.070
So no matter how far back you
go, you basically,

00:16:10.070 --> 00:16:13.602
knowing which way the stock
went 27 days ago tells you

00:16:13.602 --> 00:16:17.870
almost nothing about which way
the stock is going to go today.

00:16:17.870 --> 00:16:19.129
There's almost no correlation.
 

00:16:19.129 --> 00:16:22.754
If it went up 27 days ago,
it's statistically,

00:16:22.754 --> 00:16:26.942
over the last 7,500 days,
slightly more than half the

00:16:26.942 --> 00:16:29.600
time, it went up again today.
 

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:33.837
But such a small fraction of
the time did it go up again,

00:16:33.837 --> 00:16:37.697
the more times up than down,
that it's statistically

00:16:37.697 --> 00:16:39.058
insignificant.
 

00:16:39.058 --> 00:16:42.687
If you only do it five times,
it's going to have to be one

00:16:42.687 --> 00:16:45.018
way or the other,
so if you do it an odd number

00:16:45.018 --> 00:16:46.970
of times,
it can't be exactly even so you

00:16:46.970 --> 00:16:49.668
just figure out what the
statistical significance is.

00:16:49.668 --> 00:16:52.501
So none of them hardly,
almost none of them,

00:16:52.501 --> 00:16:54.610
are statistically significant.
 

00:16:54.610 --> 00:16:57.106
So once again,
it's not only the case that

00:16:57.106 --> 00:17:00.639
today's prices are good
forecasts of tomorrow's prices,

00:17:00.639 --> 00:17:02.772
but today's prices,
even if you add some

00:17:02.772 --> 00:17:05.932
information to it,
seem to be--even if you try to

00:17:05.932 --> 00:17:10.094
refine your set and look at only
buying stocks that 27 days ago

00:17:10.094 --> 00:17:12.752
went up,
the prices of those stocks are

00:17:12.752 --> 00:17:16.521
still going to be a reasonably
accurate forecast of tomorrow's

00:17:16.521 --> 00:17:17.140
prices.
 

00:17:17.140 --> 00:17:20.424
So I did one more experiment,
or Rashid did one more

00:17:20.424 --> 00:17:23.259
experiment for me,
in case he hears this in a

00:17:23.259 --> 00:17:23.838
year.
 

00:17:23.838 --> 00:17:31.769
He did the same thing on a
portfolio of stocks.

00:17:31.769 --> 00:17:35.328
So he looked at a 12 month
rolling average.

00:17:35.328 --> 00:17:38.144
He looked at the stocks that
had done particularly well in

00:17:38.144 --> 00:17:40.220
the past 12 months and he bought
those,

00:17:40.220 --> 00:17:42.028
and then he looked at the
stocks that had done

00:17:42.028 --> 00:17:44.640
particularly badly in the last
12 months and he shorted those,

00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:47.068
and here's what his returns
would have been,

00:17:47.068 --> 00:17:50.779
just taking the daily thing and
just adding it.

00:17:50.779 --> 00:17:53.163
And you see,
you get almost exactly back to

00:17:53.163 --> 00:17:53.390
0.
 

00:17:53.390 --> 00:17:57.029
So this was the original
compelling evidence,

00:17:57.029 --> 00:18:03.318
things like this in the 1970s
and 1980s,

00:18:03.318 --> 00:18:08.856
led people--economists--to say
that the prices of very many

00:18:08.856 --> 00:18:14.490
things seem to be very accurate
guides to future prices,

00:18:14.490 --> 00:18:22.460
and they called it rational
expectations.

00:18:22.460 --> 00:18:27.395
So the high water mark of this
theory was in 1983,

00:18:27.395 --> 00:18:32.532
I think, the most amusing
example, was Richard Roll,

00:18:32.532 --> 00:18:36.160
who taught at UCLA,
and oranges.

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:38.190
So Richard Roll did the
following experiment.

00:18:38.190 --> 00:18:42.400
He said, it turns out that for
concentrated orange juice,

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:46.472
97 percent of the oranges that
are used for concentrated orange

00:18:46.472 --> 00:18:50.348
juice are grown on trees that
are very close to Orlando,

00:18:50.348 --> 00:18:55.930
Florida, where the weather is
pretty much the same.

00:18:55.930 --> 00:18:58.607
I mean, it's a small area,
so whatever the weather is,

00:18:58.607 --> 00:19:00.630
it's that weather over the
whole area.

00:19:00.630 --> 00:19:03.453
It's amazing that so many of
the oranges are grown in the

00:19:03.453 --> 00:19:04.108
same place.
 

00:19:04.108 --> 00:19:06.420
I'm talking about concentrated
orange juice.

00:19:06.420 --> 00:19:09.190
California's no competition for
Florida.

00:19:09.190 --> 00:19:12.034
In fact, no competition for
Orlando, Florida when it comes

00:19:12.034 --> 00:19:14.778
to concentrated orange juice,
not oranges in general.

00:19:14.778 --> 00:19:19.605
So he said to himself,
"How good is the market at

00:19:19.605 --> 00:19:23.250
predicting the price of orange
juice,

00:19:23.250 --> 00:19:25.500
at predicting next period's
price of orange juice?"

00:19:25.500 --> 00:19:28.193
And he found,
just like we did here,

00:19:28.193 --> 00:19:29.578
it's quite good.
 

00:19:29.578 --> 00:19:32.146
But then he said,
"Maybe there's other

00:19:32.146 --> 00:19:35.509
information that the market
doesn't know about."

00:19:35.509 --> 00:19:39.548
So he said, "What about
the weather?"

00:19:39.548 --> 00:19:45.470
So the weather has a tremendous
effect on orange juice prices,

00:19:45.470 --> 00:19:49.484
because if it's--four hours of
freezing temperatures starts to

00:19:49.484 --> 00:19:52.601
kill the trees,
then you get less supply of

00:19:52.601 --> 00:19:55.750
oranges for the concentrated
orange juice,

00:19:55.750 --> 00:19:57.509
and then the price goes up.
 

00:19:57.509 --> 00:20:04.500
So he said, since 1970 or so,
the US Weather Bureau has spent

00:20:04.500 --> 00:20:11.842
250 million dollars building all
these weather forecasting units

00:20:11.842 --> 00:20:15.795
that make daily--
in fact, they make 36 hour,

00:20:15.795 --> 00:20:19.086
24 hour and 12 hour forecasts
of what the weather's going to

00:20:19.086 --> 00:20:20.089
be next period.
 

00:20:20.089 --> 00:20:23.660
So he said, "Really,
if the market is so good and

00:20:23.660 --> 00:20:26.960
the market price today is really
telling an uninformed investor

00:20:26.960 --> 00:20:29.088
what the price ought to be
tomorrow,

00:20:29.088 --> 00:20:32.028
let me see now,
by getting a record of the

00:20:32.028 --> 00:20:35.137
weather reports,
could I improve on the market

00:20:35.137 --> 00:20:35.558
price?
 

00:20:35.558 --> 00:20:38.223
By putting together today's
market price and the weather

00:20:38.223 --> 00:20:41.186
report today,
the weather prediction today,

00:20:41.186 --> 00:20:44.882
could I make a better forecast
of the market price

00:20:44.882 --> 00:20:46.240
tomorrow?"
 

00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:48.460
And he found out, no.
 

00:20:48.460 --> 00:20:59.522
Statistically,
the weather prices does not

00:20:59.522 --> 00:21:06.269
improve price forecast.
 

00:21:06.269 --> 00:21:07.910
So how could you interpret that?
 

00:21:07.910 --> 00:21:11.853
How could that possibly be that
knowing the weather reports

00:21:11.853 --> 00:21:15.796
doesn't help you predict the
price better the next day than

00:21:15.796 --> 00:21:17.019
today's price?
 

00:21:17.019 --> 00:21:19.930
How could that be?
 

00:21:19.930 --> 00:21:23.369
What's the obvious reason for
that?

00:21:23.369 --> 00:21:24.180
Yeah?
 

00:21:24.180 --> 00:21:27.509
Student:
&gt;

00:21:27.509 --> 00:21:28.630
Prof: Right,
so the people buying and

00:21:28.630 --> 00:21:30.318
selling, they're also looking at
the weather report,

00:21:30.318 --> 00:21:32.471
and so naturally,
they've taken that into

00:21:32.471 --> 00:21:33.009
account.
 

00:21:33.009 --> 00:21:36.092
So what it illustrates though
is that all this kind of

00:21:36.092 --> 00:21:39.522
information that you might think
would go into affecting the

00:21:39.522 --> 00:21:41.848
value of the orange juice
tomorrow,

00:21:41.848 --> 00:21:44.012
the market is already
processing that because the

00:21:44.012 --> 00:21:46.308
people buying and selling,
they're already looking at the

00:21:46.308 --> 00:21:49.288
weather report,
and they're figuring out what

00:21:49.288 --> 00:21:51.538
the right price should be.
 

00:21:51.538 --> 00:21:55.630
So that was a pretty stunning
conclusion, but he didn't want

00:21:55.630 --> 00:21:56.740
to stop there.
 

00:21:56.740 --> 00:21:59.650
So what did he do next?
 

00:21:59.650 --> 00:22:01.946
What if you were--you know how
in comp.

00:22:01.946 --> 00:22:02.308
lit.
 

00:22:02.308 --> 00:22:05.084
they always says things
backwards, the reader is

00:22:05.084 --> 00:22:08.270
detective or the detective is
reader, you know--anyway,

00:22:08.270 --> 00:22:09.275
when I took comp.
 

00:22:09.275 --> 00:22:11.576
lit., that was the gist of
every course,

00:22:11.576 --> 00:22:13.818
was to do everything backwards.
 

00:22:13.818 --> 00:22:15.891
That's how you knew you were
clever in comp.

00:22:15.891 --> 00:22:16.180
lit.
 

00:22:16.180 --> 00:22:17.382
What would a comp.
 

00:22:17.382 --> 00:22:17.650
lit.
 

00:22:17.650 --> 00:22:18.920
person have done?
 

00:22:18.920 --> 00:22:19.660
Yes?
 

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:21.280
Student:
Used the price to predict the

00:22:21.280 --> 00:22:21.650
weather.
 

00:22:21.650 --> 00:22:24.436
Prof: He said,
"Let's use the price to

00:22:24.436 --> 00:22:26.028
predict the weather."
 

00:22:26.028 --> 00:22:31.583
So he'd said,
suppose the price today turned

00:22:31.583 --> 00:22:38.816
out to be higher than the
price--okay, so--the price from

00:22:38.816 --> 00:22:44.500
yesterday to today went
unexpectedly up.

00:22:44.500 --> 00:22:46.640
It went unexpectedly up.
 

00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:49.145
Then he said,
"Okay, that means these

00:22:49.145 --> 00:22:53.058
market guys were surprised today
to see the price go up."

00:22:53.058 --> 00:22:55.990
There's a weather forecast back
here as well,

00:22:55.990 --> 00:22:57.980
and there's a weather forecast
here,

00:22:57.980 --> 00:23:02.954
and he said,
maybe you can now say if the

00:23:02.954 --> 00:23:06.300
price went up--
can you use that to now

00:23:06.300 --> 00:23:07.480
forecast the weather?
 

00:23:07.480 --> 00:23:11.000
So he said, suppose that
whatever the forecast is here,

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:12.990
you now say since the price
went up,

00:23:12.990 --> 00:23:16.358
we're now going to forecast
that the weather guys--

00:23:16.358 --> 00:23:18.961
the price going up means
they've learned something here

00:23:18.961 --> 00:23:20.838
about the weather probably being
bad.

00:23:20.838 --> 00:23:22.961
So the question is,
did the weatherman learn the

00:23:22.961 --> 00:23:23.548
same thing?
 

00:23:23.548 --> 00:23:26.672
So he says, "Let's test
the hypothesis that when the

00:23:26.672 --> 00:23:29.298
price went up,
these guys learned more about

00:23:29.298 --> 00:23:31.960
the weather than the weather
predictors did,

00:23:31.960 --> 00:23:34.796
so that in fact the actual
weather from this prediction is

00:23:34.796 --> 00:23:36.089
likely to go down."
 

00:23:36.089 --> 00:23:40.358
And that's just what he found.
 

00:23:40.358 --> 00:23:44.098
You can't use weather to
improve the price prediction of

00:23:44.098 --> 00:23:47.634
prices, but you can use prices
to improve the weather

00:23:47.634 --> 00:23:50.150
prediction of the weather
people.

00:23:50.150 --> 00:23:55.153
That was one of those stunning
confirmations of the rational

00:23:55.153 --> 00:23:59.478
expectations hypothesis,
so what could explain that,

00:23:59.478 --> 00:24:00.750
by the way?
 

00:24:00.750 --> 00:24:05.829
Is that just crazy or an
accident, or is there some

00:24:05.829 --> 00:24:08.980
logical explanation for that?
 

00:24:08.980 --> 00:24:09.690
Yeah?
 

00:24:09.690 --> 00:24:11.848
Student:
People buying and selling

00:24:11.848 --> 00:24:13.683
oranges know more about the
weather

00:24:13.683 --> 00:24:15.250
&gt;
 

00:24:15.250 --> 00:24:16.278
Prof: Than the
government does.

00:24:16.278 --> 00:24:18.884
So the people buying and
selling oranges,

00:24:18.884 --> 00:24:22.400
this is billions of dollars of
money changing hands.

00:24:22.400 --> 00:24:25.526
The government spent 250
million dollars in this area

00:24:25.526 --> 00:24:27.088
forecasting the weather.
 

00:24:27.088 --> 00:24:28.588
These guys have billions at
stake.

00:24:28.588 --> 00:24:32.409
They in fact have better
weather forecasting technology

00:24:32.409 --> 00:24:35.403
than the government does,
and they're making better

00:24:35.403 --> 00:24:37.390
forecasts than the government is
of the weather.

00:24:37.390 --> 00:24:39.473
So if you ask them,
they would know better than the

00:24:39.473 --> 00:24:41.724
government what the weather's
going to be the next day,

00:24:41.724 --> 00:24:43.058
and the price reflects that.
 

00:24:43.058 --> 00:24:47.220
Okay, so that's the efficient
markets hypothesis,

00:24:47.220 --> 00:24:50.470
which seduced many in the
economics profession,

00:24:50.470 --> 00:24:53.210
and there's still a tremendous
amount of truth to it,

00:24:53.210 --> 00:24:56.346
at least at the level--if you
don't know anything and you want

00:24:56.346 --> 00:24:58.299
to know something about the
future,

00:24:58.299 --> 00:24:59.558
look at the prices today.
 

00:24:59.558 --> 00:25:02.286
That's going to tell you a
tremendous amount about the

00:25:02.286 --> 00:25:02.750
future.
 

00:25:02.750 --> 00:25:07.028
Now the question is whether
it's as precise as Roll seems to

00:25:07.028 --> 00:25:11.380
suggest, and we're going to see
that it's not going to be.

00:25:11.380 --> 00:25:15.048
But anyway, for a while,
these people,

00:25:15.048 --> 00:25:18.067
the rational expectations
school, which is mostly in

00:25:18.067 --> 00:25:19.948
Chicago,
they had the view,

00:25:19.948 --> 00:25:22.269
and Fama was one of the
leaders,

00:25:22.269 --> 00:25:25.701
they had the view that this
rational expectations pricing

00:25:25.701 --> 00:25:29.500
was the best-documented truth in
all of the social sciences.

00:25:29.500 --> 00:25:30.990
That was what Fama said.
 

00:25:30.990 --> 00:25:34.769
So we'll have to come back to
see that that's not always the

00:25:34.769 --> 00:25:37.910
case, but certainly looks good
in these graphs.

00:25:37.910 --> 00:25:42.250
Okay, that's the first idea.
 

00:25:42.250 --> 00:25:45.914
Now the next idea that we
looked at was,

00:25:45.914 --> 00:25:50.710
what is the most important
thing to be uncertain?

00:25:50.710 --> 00:25:54.674
Well, there's output that
you're uncertain about,

00:25:54.674 --> 00:25:58.721
but the next most important
thing is the discount,

00:25:58.721 --> 00:26:00.538
the interest rate.
 

00:26:00.538 --> 00:26:03.002
After all, that's the most
important variable in the whole

00:26:03.002 --> 00:26:04.298
economy according to Fisher.
 

00:26:04.298 --> 00:26:12.710
Who's to say the discount is
always exactly the same thing,

00:26:12.710 --> 00:26:16.480
so, uncertain discounts.
 

00:26:16.480 --> 00:26:19.430
So now we said--and you've done
in the problem set--

00:26:19.430 --> 00:26:21.769
if the interest rate is 100
percent,

00:26:21.769 --> 00:26:23.858
it might go up to 200 percent,
say,

00:26:23.858 --> 00:26:30.263
or it might go down to 50
percent, and now you want to

00:26:30.263 --> 00:26:32.699
ask,
what's the value of 1 dollar

00:26:32.699 --> 00:26:33.038
here?
 

00:26:33.038 --> 00:26:35.833
It's a little subtler,
because here,

00:26:35.833 --> 00:26:40.622
the expectation was all that
mattered, the expectation of the

00:26:40.622 --> 00:26:41.578
payoffs.
 

00:26:41.578 --> 00:26:45.202
If I change this to 106,
and I change this to 96,

00:26:45.202 --> 00:26:48.901
I haven't changed the
expectation, so the price is

00:26:48.901 --> 00:26:50.940
going to stay the same.
 

00:26:50.940 --> 00:26:53.740
So the variance has nothing to
do with what the price is.

00:26:53.740 --> 00:26:55.920
But things can get subtler.
 

00:26:55.920 --> 00:26:59.670
Let's suppose that what's
changing is the discount rate.

00:26:59.670 --> 00:27:03.808
Now the variance is going to
have a big effect on what the

00:27:03.808 --> 00:27:05.480
values of things are.
 

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:08.221
So if we think this is
happening with 50:50

00:27:08.221 --> 00:27:11.880
probability, the guy--so what do
I mean by this model?

00:27:11.880 --> 00:27:15.384
Today you know that the value
of something tomorrow is going

00:27:15.384 --> 00:27:17.818
to be 1 half of what it pays
tomorrow,

00:27:17.818 --> 00:27:20.309
up 1 half what it pays tomorrow
down,

00:27:20.309 --> 00:27:22.528
discounted by 100 percent.
 

00:27:22.528 --> 00:27:25.107
Tomorrow, you're not sure
whether you're going to be

00:27:25.107 --> 00:27:28.038
discounting it 200 percent or
discounting it 50 percent.

00:27:28.038 --> 00:27:33.551
So then the value today is
going to be 1 over (1 100

00:27:33.551 --> 00:27:40.232
percent),
times (1 half times 1 over (1

00:27:40.232 --> 00:27:51.930
200 percent) of 1 1 half times 1
over (1 50 percent) times 1).

00:27:51.930 --> 00:27:54.142
Because over here,
you know that this dollar's

00:27:54.142 --> 00:27:56.108
only going to be worth 1 third
to you.

00:27:56.108 --> 00:27:58.496
Over here, you know this
dollar's going to be worth 2

00:27:58.496 --> 00:27:58.910
thirds.
 

00:27:58.910 --> 00:28:02.450
So that's the 2 thirds here and
the 1 third here,

00:28:02.450 --> 00:28:05.048
and there's a 50:50 chance of
each of these,

00:28:05.048 --> 00:28:08.180
and you're going to discount it
by 1 over 100 percent,

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:11.720
so that's what the value is to
you today.

00:28:11.720 --> 00:28:15.255
So now you did a problem set
where you had to do a bunch of

00:28:15.255 --> 00:28:16.170
these things.
 

00:28:16.170 --> 00:28:20.402
We're going to call that D(2),
because that's what you would

00:28:20.402 --> 00:28:24.848
pay today to get 1 dollar for
sure at time 2 in the future,

00:28:24.848 --> 00:28:31.960
and D(1) is going to be just 1
over (1 100 percent),

00:28:31.960 --> 00:28:34.680
which is 1 half,
which is what you would pay

00:28:34.680 --> 00:28:37.400
today to get 1 dollar for sure
at time 1.

00:28:37.400 --> 00:28:41.984
And I could compute D(3),
and any other D that I wanted

00:28:41.984 --> 00:28:42.410
to.
 

00:28:42.410 --> 00:28:45.634
Okay, so we're going to see
that interest rate uncertainty

00:28:45.634 --> 00:28:48.519
is the most important
uncertainty in the economy.

00:28:48.519 --> 00:28:50.548
The value of everything is
going to change.

00:28:50.548 --> 00:28:53.523
If the interest rates go up,
all the bonds are going to go

00:28:53.523 --> 00:28:54.358
down in value.
 

00:28:54.358 --> 00:28:56.775
All the mortgages are going to
change in value,

00:28:56.775 --> 00:28:59.608
although sometimes they go in
surprising directions.

00:28:59.608 --> 00:29:02.031
But everything's going to
change in value when the

00:29:02.031 --> 00:29:03.118
interest rate moves.
 

00:29:03.118 --> 00:29:05.615
That's going to subject
everybody to tremendous amounts

00:29:05.615 --> 00:29:08.386
of risk and we have to figure
out, how are they going to cope

00:29:08.386 --> 00:29:09.450
with all that risk?
 

00:29:09.450 --> 00:29:12.438
Before we answer that question,
we want to answer the simpler

00:29:12.438 --> 00:29:14.778
question, how are they going to
value things?

00:29:14.778 --> 00:29:18.078
And here we just have the same
tree that we had before.

00:29:18.078 --> 00:29:20.999
So that's what we did last
class, and I just wanted to

00:29:20.999 --> 00:29:23.753
finish that thought,
which I didn't get a chance to

00:29:23.753 --> 00:29:24.140
do.
 

00:29:24.140 --> 00:29:28.924
So for period 3,
we could have done a 3 period

00:29:28.924 --> 00:29:35.730
thing and assumed that this went
up to 400 percent and would have

00:29:35.730 --> 00:29:40.730
gone to 100 percent or down to
25 percent,

00:29:40.730 --> 00:29:44.640
and then still paid 1,1, 1.
 

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:47.020
Okay, so that's payoff for 1
dollar for sure,

00:29:47.020 --> 00:29:49.998
but now we've got still more
uncertainty in the interest

00:29:49.998 --> 00:29:50.538
rates.
 

00:29:50.538 --> 00:29:54.220
So you figured out in the
problem set what the value of

00:29:54.220 --> 00:29:56.808
that's going to be and you got
D(3).

00:29:56.808 --> 00:30:00.833
So I could have done this for
D(4) and any other T that I

00:30:00.833 --> 00:30:04.778
wanted to and in fact,
that's also what you did in the

00:30:04.778 --> 00:30:08.940
problem set,
you did it for all the way up

00:30:08.940 --> 00:30:10.038
to D(30).
 

00:30:10.038 --> 00:30:14.910
Okay, so I want now to just say
one thing about the environment,

00:30:14.910 --> 00:30:17.374
before--we're going to come
back and analyze this over and

00:30:17.374 --> 00:30:19.969
over again to see the risk the
whole economy's exposed to and

00:30:19.969 --> 00:30:22.778
how people cope with that risk
with interest rates changing,

00:30:22.778 --> 00:30:25.328
but I want to make one
observation.

00:30:25.328 --> 00:30:28.123
These numbers,
D(1), D(2), D(3),

00:30:28.123 --> 00:30:33.440
D(4), they reflect people's
attitudes towards the future.

00:30:33.440 --> 00:30:35.750
What would you pay today to get
1 dollar at time 1?

00:30:35.750 --> 00:30:37.680
What would pay today to get 1
dollar at time 2?

00:30:37.680 --> 00:30:40.410
What would you pay today to get
1 dollar at time 3?

00:30:40.410 --> 00:30:42.769
So what is the shape of that
function?

00:30:42.769 --> 00:30:47.115
Well, in the case of certainty,
with a constant discount rate,

00:30:47.115 --> 00:30:50.818
that function would have to
decline exponentially.

00:30:50.818 --> 00:31:00.289
So it would be an exponential
decline.

00:31:00.289 --> 00:31:00.808
Why?
 

00:31:00.808 --> 00:31:05.068
Because this would be equal to
1 over (1 r),

00:31:05.068 --> 00:31:08.838
and this would be equal to 1
over (1 r) squared,

00:31:08.838 --> 00:31:12.692
and this would be equal to 1
over (1 r) to the fourth,

00:31:12.692 --> 00:31:13.130
etc.
 

00:31:13.130 --> 00:31:17.308
So after 100 years or 500
years, you wouldn't care,

00:31:17.308 --> 00:31:20.653
as long as r is .03 or
something percent,

00:31:20.653 --> 00:31:22.660
.03, r is 3 percent.
 

00:31:22.660 --> 00:31:25.570
As long as it's a number like 2
percent or 3 percent,

00:31:25.570 --> 00:31:27.922
after 500 years,
you just don't care at all

00:31:27.922 --> 00:31:29.769
about what's going to happen.
 

00:31:29.769 --> 00:31:31.299
If the whole economy,
the society,

00:31:31.299 --> 00:31:33.805
is discounting the future and
trading it off like this,

00:31:33.805 --> 00:31:35.798
you don't care at all about the
future.

00:31:35.798 --> 00:31:39.916
So environmental improvements
today, which don't have an

00:31:39.916 --> 00:31:43.510
effect for 200 years,
would be regarded as stupid

00:31:43.510 --> 00:31:44.259
ideas.
 

00:31:44.259 --> 00:31:47.669
And environmentalists have been
trying desperately to make an

00:31:47.669 --> 00:31:50.509
argument that 200 years from now
really matters.

00:31:50.509 --> 00:31:52.400
So of course,
they argue about the interest

00:31:52.400 --> 00:31:53.920
rate,
but really, all they're doing

00:31:53.920 --> 00:31:55.680
is they're arguing that the
interest rate,

00:31:55.680 --> 00:31:58.375
instead of being 3 percent
should be 1 percent or something

00:31:58.375 --> 00:32:01.548
like that,
and that's not really helping,

00:32:01.548 --> 00:32:05.284
because even 1 percent,
if you keep doing that for 500

00:32:05.284 --> 00:32:06.967
years,
you're going to get a pretty

00:32:06.967 --> 00:32:08.180
trivial number by the end.
 

00:32:08.180 --> 00:32:13.269
So let me ask you the following
question.

00:32:13.269 --> 00:32:17.777
Suppose you could have 15
dollars today,

00:32:17.777 --> 00:32:24.711
or--so this is an experiment
Thaler ran, who was a behavioral

00:32:24.711 --> 00:32:26.328
economist.
 

00:32:26.328 --> 00:32:35.298
So, next month,
1 year and 10 years.

00:32:35.298 --> 00:32:39.406
How much money would you want
next month instead of the 15

00:32:39.406 --> 00:32:40.558
dollars today?
 

00:32:40.558 --> 00:32:42.819
Somebody give a number,
shout out a number.

00:32:42.819 --> 00:32:45.390
What seems equivalent to you?
 

00:32:45.390 --> 00:32:46.298
20.
 

00:32:46.298 --> 00:32:50.438
It happens to be exactly what
the average--do you know the

00:32:50.438 --> 00:32:51.890
Thaler experiment?
 

00:32:51.890 --> 00:32:53.640
That's precisely the average.
 

00:32:53.640 --> 00:32:56.907
Thaler did a class like this,
averaged all the numbers,

00:32:56.907 --> 00:32:58.298
he got 20, amazingly.
 

00:32:58.298 --> 00:33:02.089
What about for 1 year,
what would you say?

00:33:02.089 --> 00:33:08.890
50 to 100.
 

00:33:08.890 --> 00:33:11.130
And what about 10 years?
 

00:33:11.130 --> 00:33:14.130
200.
 

00:33:14.130 --> 00:33:16.240
Okay, so I'll tell you the
Thaler numbers.

00:33:16.240 --> 00:33:18.059
I stupidly forgot them all.
 

00:33:18.059 --> 00:33:23.440
What a turkey.
 

00:33:23.440 --> 00:33:30.558
Okay, so the numbers of
Thaler--let's just go with those

00:33:30.558 --> 00:33:37.420
numbers, but what do you think
about those numbers?

00:33:37.420 --> 00:33:43.717
So Thaler got--it's
amazing--Thaler got 20,50 and

00:33:43.717 --> 00:33:50.801
100 were Thaler's numbers,
so very close to what you're

00:33:50.801 --> 00:33:52.769
telling me.
 

00:33:52.769 --> 00:33:54.180
50 and 100.
 

00:33:54.180 --> 00:33:57.609
So what's the matter with those
numbers.

00:33:57.609 --> 00:33:58.848
Let's go with Thaler's.
 

00:33:58.848 --> 00:34:01.288
They weren't that different
from yours.

00:34:01.288 --> 00:34:12.280
What's the problem with
Thaler's numbers?

00:34:12.280 --> 00:34:15.989
Student:
&gt;

00:34:15.989 --> 00:34:17.659
Prof: Rapidly, rapidly.
 

00:34:17.659 --> 00:34:18.960
This is just one month.
 

00:34:18.960 --> 00:34:21.505
You have to have a huge
discount to care--this

00:34:21.505 --> 00:34:24.900
is--you're discounting by 33
percent or something a month.

00:34:24.900 --> 00:34:27.199
It's a tremendous discount to
go from here to here.

00:34:27.199 --> 00:34:31.679
If you did that 12 times--so if
you look at the monthly discount

00:34:31.679 --> 00:34:34.880
rate from here to here,
you get 33 percent.

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:37.188
From here to here,
it's to the 12^(th) power,

00:34:37.188 --> 00:34:39.130
so you're discounting by 5
percent.

00:34:39.130 --> 00:34:42.797
From here to here,
you've got the 120^(th) power,

00:34:42.797 --> 00:34:47.001
so what number to the 120^(th)
gives you 6 and 2 thirds,

00:34:47.001 --> 00:34:48.989
not a very big number.
 

00:34:48.989 --> 00:34:55.875
In fact, the reciprocal of that
number is the discount,

00:34:55.875 --> 00:34:58.170
is .75 to the 1.
 

00:34:58.170 --> 00:35:07.699
So this is .75 obviously,
and then (15 over 50) to the 1

00:35:07.699 --> 00:35:17.231
tenth--1 twelfth--is .9,
and then (15 over 100) to the 1

00:35:17.231 --> 00:35:20.869
twentieth is .98.
 

00:35:20.869 --> 00:35:24.342
So you're discounting by 33
percent, something like that,

00:35:24.342 --> 00:35:26.699
by 10 percent and then by 2
percent.

00:35:26.699 --> 00:35:30.969
So your discount rate is
falling rapidly.

00:35:30.969 --> 00:35:34.518
You do experiments with
animals, you get the same

00:35:34.518 --> 00:35:35.480
conclusion.
 

00:35:35.480 --> 00:35:39.547
You ask the animals--you can
make an animal work and then

00:35:39.547 --> 00:35:43.469
they'll have to wait a certain
time to get the food.

00:35:43.469 --> 00:35:46.992
Or if they work harder,
they can get more food,

00:35:46.992 --> 00:35:50.670
but they have to wait a longer
amount of time.

00:35:50.670 --> 00:35:52.030
So you try and do the
experiment.

00:35:52.030 --> 00:35:54.380
I'm not sure these actually are
believable,

00:35:54.380 --> 00:35:57.307
but anyway, they do these
experiments and they figure out

00:35:57.307 --> 00:35:59.956
how much the animal is --
you know, these are birds and

00:35:59.956 --> 00:36:04.190
mice and all kinds of things--
trading off waiting for getting

00:36:04.190 --> 00:36:07.641
a bigger reward,
and they get the similar kinds

00:36:07.641 --> 00:36:10.929
of numbers to what Thaler got by
talking to psychological

00:36:10.929 --> 00:36:12.809
experiments with real people.
 

00:36:12.809 --> 00:36:14.489
How can you explain it?
 

00:36:14.489 --> 00:36:17.347
In the world of constant
discounting, you couldn't

00:36:17.347 --> 00:36:18.630
possibly explain it.
 

00:36:18.630 --> 00:36:22.115
Now of course,
you could explain it by saying,

00:36:22.115 --> 00:36:26.610
"Everybody's discount rate
is going to get smaller and

00:36:26.610 --> 00:36:28.780
smaller over time."
 

00:36:28.780 --> 00:36:32.483
Their annual discount rate is
getting smaller and smaller over

00:36:32.483 --> 00:36:32.909
time.
 

00:36:32.909 --> 00:36:35.012
But that's totally
unbelievable,

00:36:35.012 --> 00:36:35.760
you know.
 

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:39.722
It's just, you know that 1 year
from now, if you were asked the

00:36:39.722 --> 00:36:42.981
same kinds of questions,
you'd give the same kind of

00:36:42.981 --> 00:36:43.750
answers.
 

00:36:43.750 --> 00:36:47.784
So your discount between today
and next month is going to be

00:36:47.784 --> 00:36:50.110
the same next year as it is now.
 

00:36:50.110 --> 00:36:53.454
So it's not the case that the 1
month discount happens to be

00:36:53.454 --> 00:36:55.610
high now because you're in
college,

00:36:55.610 --> 00:36:57.260
and then the day you get out of
college,

00:36:57.260 --> 00:36:59.186
you're going to be more mature
and so you're going to have a

00:36:59.186 --> 00:36:59.969
smaller discount rate.
 

00:36:59.969 --> 00:37:01.670
When you get to my age,
you're going to be even more

00:37:01.670 --> 00:37:03.070
mature and have a smaller
discount rate.

00:37:03.070 --> 00:37:04.219
That doesn't happen.
 

00:37:04.219 --> 00:37:06.199
The discount rate doesn't go
down like that.

00:37:06.199 --> 00:37:07.766
In fact, if anything,
if you're rational,

00:37:07.766 --> 00:37:08.550
it ought to go up.
 

00:37:08.550 --> 00:37:10.119
I'm closer to death than you
are.

00:37:10.119 --> 00:37:12.427
If I don't get the stuff now,
who knows when I'll ever get

00:37:12.427 --> 00:37:12.630
it?
 

00:37:12.630 --> 00:37:15.135
So the discount rate should be
going up, not going down,

00:37:15.135 --> 00:37:17.778
and yet it seems like there's
so much evidence that it goes

00:37:17.778 --> 00:37:18.190
down.
 

00:37:18.190 --> 00:37:21.969
So this is a big puzzle in
economics.

00:37:21.969 --> 00:37:24.797
So I just offer,
again, I'm going to make a

00:37:24.797 --> 00:37:26.750
habit of offering theories.
 

00:37:26.750 --> 00:37:28.210
I'm not saying this is the
right theory.

00:37:28.210 --> 00:37:31.626
I'm just simply pointing out
that if you had this random

00:37:31.626 --> 00:37:34.297
discount, put uncertainty into
the discount,

00:37:34.297 --> 00:37:37.030
put uncertainty into the
interest rates.

00:37:37.030 --> 00:37:40.420
Uncertainty in the interest
rates is the heart of finance.

00:37:40.420 --> 00:37:44.405
Every single person,
every single serious finance

00:37:44.405 --> 00:37:48.724
person, thinks about--what do
you call it?--uncertain

00:37:48.724 --> 00:37:51.550
variability in interest rates.
 

00:37:51.550 --> 00:37:54.840
So I take the simplest possible
process, where the interest

00:37:54.840 --> 00:37:57.619
rates can go up or down by the
same percentage.

00:37:57.619 --> 00:38:01.980
So for example,
you could start at 4 percent,

00:38:01.980 --> 00:38:08.706
and then the variation or the
standard deviation could be 16

00:38:08.706 --> 00:38:12.204
percent,
which means that 4 percent

00:38:12.204 --> 00:38:16.778
basically goes to 4 percent
times 1.16 or to 4 percent

00:38:16.778 --> 00:38:18.420
divided by 1.16.
 

00:38:18.420 --> 00:38:24.114
That process actually,
times e to the .16 or times e

00:38:24.114 --> 00:38:27.840
to the -.16,
which is very close to times

00:38:27.840 --> 00:38:32.530
1.16, that geometric random walk
is the basic model of finance.

00:38:32.530 --> 00:38:35.423
And what you found in your
homework is, you were supposed

00:38:35.423 --> 00:38:37.853
to find, that as you go out
further and further,

00:38:37.853 --> 00:38:40.179
the effective discount rate
does go down.

00:38:40.179 --> 00:38:42.349
And what I forgot to say,
the punch line,

00:38:42.349 --> 00:38:46.980
Thaler's numbers here confirm
what all the behavioral

00:38:46.980 --> 00:38:51.351
economists suggest,
which is that there's

00:38:51.351 --> 00:38:54.110
hyperbolic discounting.
 

00:38:54.110 --> 00:39:00.085
So what they confirmed in these
experiments is that if this is

00:39:00.085 --> 00:39:03.625
D(t),
this should go down like t to

00:39:03.625 --> 00:39:08.068
some power,
you know, t to the - some

00:39:08.068 --> 00:39:13.329
power, t to the -2 or t to the
-1 half,

00:39:13.329 --> 00:39:14.610
or something like that.
 

00:39:14.610 --> 00:39:21.472
They don't pin down what this
number is, but t to the -a,

00:39:21.472 --> 00:39:26.987
so it goes down much slower
than the exponent,

00:39:26.987 --> 00:39:32.380
which is some exponent like .9
to the t.

00:39:32.380 --> 00:39:34.119
That goes down much faster than
that does.

00:39:34.119 --> 00:39:35.699
This is a polynomial in t.
 

00:39:35.699 --> 00:39:37.250
This is an exponential in t.
 

00:39:37.250 --> 00:39:39.139
So it's going down much faster.
 

00:39:39.139 --> 00:39:42.494
So this is a classic--Thaler's
numbers are a classic

00:39:42.494 --> 00:39:43.349
polynomial.
 

00:39:43.349 --> 00:39:45.599
In fact, with exponent 1 half.
 

00:39:45.599 --> 00:39:50.266
Thaler's numbers fit t to the
-1 half, if you do the right

00:39:50.266 --> 00:39:51.659
starting point.
 

00:39:51.659 --> 00:39:54.050
So what did I show?
 

00:39:54.050 --> 00:39:56.610
I showed that any geometric
random walk,

00:39:56.610 --> 00:39:59.199
no matter where you start,
no matter what r(0) is,

00:39:59.199 --> 00:40:01.690
no matter what you start,
no matter what standard

00:40:01.690 --> 00:40:04.027
deviation you go,
if you figure out the sequence

00:40:04.027 --> 00:40:05.836
of numbers,
D(1), D(2), D(3),

00:40:05.836 --> 00:40:09.097
D(4), not up to 30 years,
which is where everybody else

00:40:09.097 --> 00:40:11.237
stopped,
because bonds end at 30 years,

00:40:11.237 --> 00:40:13.389
but you do it for 100 or 200 or
500,

00:40:13.389 --> 00:40:18.907
D(t) is always eventually going
to be equal to some constant

00:40:18.907 --> 00:40:22.927
times t to the -1 half,
exactly consistent with

00:40:22.927 --> 00:40:24.170
Thaler's numbers.
 

00:40:24.170 --> 00:40:26.369
So I don't know if that's the
explanation for hyperbolic

00:40:26.369 --> 00:40:28.088
discounting,
but I thought it was pretty

00:40:28.088 --> 00:40:30.583
interesting,
and anyone could have done it

00:40:30.583 --> 00:40:33.159
if they just didn't stop at 30
years,

00:40:33.159 --> 00:40:34.429
just kept going.
 

00:40:34.429 --> 00:40:37.655
And then there's some
mathematics, you could compute

00:40:37.655 --> 00:40:40.882
examples, but there's some
mathematics to prove that

00:40:40.882 --> 00:40:43.730
asymptotically,
that's the right formula.

00:40:43.730 --> 00:40:46.945
Okay, so in fact this paper,
I wrote this with a co-author,

00:40:46.945 --> 00:40:49.273
Doyne Farmer,
whose daughter is a sophomore

00:40:49.273 --> 00:40:51.989
here and whose son just
graduated by the way.

00:40:51.989 --> 00:40:55.570
He's in Santa Fe.
 

